  <thingsToDo><![CDATA[<p style="color: #00533a;"><strong>Things to see and do</strong></p>
<p>Peschiera’s train station makes it perfect for a sightseeing holiday. You and your family can hop on a train and be in Verona in around 15 minutes and Venice in under two hours. Don’t overlook the smaller cities though – both Padua and Vicenza are fantastic places to visit.</p>
<p>Use the ferries to explore the rest of Lake Garda, regular services run to <a data-udi="umb://document/59fcac55a66d4666ae4b0cca449364d1" href="/{localLink:umb://document/59fcac55a66d4666ae4b0cca449364d1}" title="Bardolino">Bardolino</a> where you can sit by the lake with a glass of rose for lunch. Or you might want to spend the day in <a data-udi="umb://document/93a0ea3cd0334ca088eaf788bad0faba" href="/{localLink:umb://document/93a0ea3cd0334ca088eaf788bad0faba}" title="Sirmione">Sirmione</a> – make sure you try the ice cream if you go! There’s plenty to explore in Peschiera itself too. We like walking along the 16th century walls and heading out to visit the nearby vineyards and olive groves.</p>
<p style="color: #00533a;"><strong>Food &amp; drink</strong></p>
<p>A trip to Italy just wouldn’t be the same with joining the locals for aperitivo. If you’re down by Peschiera’s harbour at around 6pm, drop into Tortuga restaurant. The prices are reasonable and you get good views of the lake.</p>
<p style="color: #00533a;"><strong>Activities</strong></p>
<p>Peschiera is a good starting point for cycling along the promenades and making your way around the lake. Do it all or split it into parts by using the ferries. The route to Mantova is the main attraction for cyclists– it runs through Micio park and is well signposted for the whole 42 kilometres.</p>
<p>Your children will love the theme parks that Peschiera has to offer. Gardaland' huge and full of things to do, from aquariums to rollercoasters and water rides. If you're really feeling the heat then a great place to cool off is Caneva Aquapark; it's an aquatic paradise!</p>]]></thingsToDo>
